    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory. For each file, compute and return a compact summary with these fields: file_name, row_count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, unique_cmdb_ids (list up to 20), and unique_key_names (for metric.csv use kpi_name; for trace.csv use trace_name; for log.csv use log_name; for error_logs.csv return nothing for key names). Additionally, for metric.csv return the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs ranked by count with their counts. Keep outputs compact and limit lists to at most 20 entries. Do not print full raw tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded all four telemetry files and produced a compact summary. Key findings: metric.csv is large (321,027 rows) and covers 2022-03-20 21:00:00 to 22:00:00 (UTC+8), while trace.csv and log.csv cover the incident window (21:30–22:00). error_logs.csv is empty. The top (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv are dominated by shippingservice2-0 metrics (multiple container.node-6.* and mesh.* KPIs) with 61 records each, indicating these metrics are frequent in the dataset. To follow the prescribed workflow, we must next compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series (using the full available series in metric.csv) before filtering to the failure window. These thresholds will be used for anomaly detection in the incident period. No root cause has been decided yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and compute global summary statistics per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair using the full available data (do NOT filter by time window). For each pair compute: count, min_timestamp (full series), max_timestamp (full series), p50 (median) of value, p95 of value, and p99 of value. Return a compact result containing only the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs ranked by count with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, p50, p95, p99. Also return the total number of unique cmdb_id values and total number of unique kpi_name values in metric.csv. Limit all lists/rows to at most 20 entries."
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed global percentiles (p50/p95/p99) for the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv and observed the top-volume records are all from shippingservice2-0 covering the full hour. We still need global thresholds for all component-KPI pairs (not just top20), then to filter metric data to the incident window (2022-03-20 21:30:00 to 2022-03-20 22:00:00 UTC+8) and detect anomalies relative to those global thresholds. The next step must therefore: (1) compute global thresholds (p95 and p05) for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full metric.csv series, (2) filter metric records to the incident window, (3) mark anomalies as high (value >= p95) or low (value <= p05), and (4) return a compact ranked list of candidate component-KPIs with anomalies for further inspection. No root cause has been determined yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, first compute global thresholds for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair over the full available data (do NOT filter by time). For each pair compute p95 and p05. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2022-03-20 21:30:00 to 2022-03-20 22:00:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in the window, compute: count_in_window, anomaly_count_high = number of rows with value >= p95, anomaly_count_low = number of rows with value <= p05, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (the earliest timestamp in the window where either condition holds). Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs ranked by total anomaly_count (anomaly_count_high + anomaly_count_low) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_in_window, anomaly_count_high, anomaly_count_low, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, p05, p95. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv and the total number of pairs that have total_anomaly_count > 0 in the window. Limit all returned rows to at most 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds (p95/p05) per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric.csv and then flagged anomalies in the incident window (2022-03-20 21:30:00 to 22:00:00 UTC+8). The anomaly scan returned a very large number of flagged pairs: 5209 of 5281 pairs had at least one anomaly in the window. Many top pairs (examples) are from adservice and show every point in the window flagged (count_in_window=31) with earliest anomaly at 21:30:00+08:00. This wide spread of anomalies means we must aggregate anomalies to component level to narrow candidates and find coherent fault periods (consecutive anomalies) and earliest occurrence times that could correspond to the two failures. We still need to: (1) find which components (services/pods/nodes) have the largest anomaly burden and their earliest anomalous timestamps; (2) from those candidates, inspect traces and logs to distinguish root cause components and reasons. No root cause identified yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the anomaly results you already computed for metric.csv in the incident window (use the kernel table produced in the previous step), aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id. For each cmdb_id compute: total_anomaly_count = sum(total_anomaly_count across its kpis), total_pairs_with_anomaly = count of distinct kpi_name with total_anomaly_count>0, sum_anomaly_high, sum_anomaly_low, and earliest_anom_ts (earliest among its kpis). Return a compact table of the top 20 cmdb_id sorted by total_anomaly_count with columns: cmdb_id, total_anomaly_count, total_pairs_with_anomaly, sum_anomaly_high, sum_anomaly_low, earliest_anom_ts. Also return the total number of distinct cmdb_id that had any anomaly in the window. Limit output to at most 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metric anomalies by cmdb_id for the incident window and found very large anomaly volumes across many services. Top cmdb_ids (by total_anomaly_count) are adservice, adservice2, various frontends, checkoutservice instances, productcatalogservice instances, and recommendationservice instances. The earliest anomalies for top components are at 2022-03-20 21:30:00+08:00, but we still do not know whether there were one or two distinct failure events inside the 21:30–22:00 window, nor which specific component(s) and resource(s) triggered each failure. To proceed we must (1) identify the precise timestamps when anomalies peaked (candidate failure occurrence times) by looking at anomaly counts aggregated per-minute across all component-KPI pairs, and (2) for the top candidate components, find which specific minute timestamps show the most KPI anomalies for that component (these will help pinpoint fault start times and which component’s KPIs turned anomalous first). After we get those timestamps (global peaks and per-component peak minutes), we will use trace.csv and log.csv around those peak minutes to disambiguate root cause component(s) and reason(s).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric anomaly results already stored in the kernel (the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomaly flags within the incident window 2022-03-20 21:30:00 to 2022-03-20 22:00:00 UTC+8), do the following two compact aggregations:\n1) Global per-minute anomaly peaks: compute total_anomaly_count at each timestamp (sum of anomalies across all component-KPI pairs for that minute). Return the top 10 timestamps sorted by total_anomaly_count with columns: timestamp, total_anomaly_count.\n2) Per-top-component peak minutes: take the top 10 cmdb_id from the previously computed cmdb-level aggregation (kernel variable top20_cmdb). For each of these 10 cmdb_id, compute for each timestamp in the window the number of distinct kpi_name that are anomalous at that timestamp. Return the top 3 timestamps per cmdb_id by that per-minute anomalous_kpi_count with columns: cmdb_id, timestamp, anomalous_kpi_count. Limit all outputs to the requested rows only (top 10 timestamps for part 1; up to 30 rows for part 2)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed preprocess and anomaly detection: global thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi) were computed from full metric.csv, metric data were filtered to the incident window (2022-03-20 21:30:00 to 22:00:00 UTC+8), and anomalies flagged (value >= p95 or <= p05). Aggregating anomalies by minute produced clear anomaly peaks: the highest anomaly minutes are around 21:59–22:00 and several other high-count minutes (21:54–21:57, 21:50, etc.). Aggregating by cmdb_id shows very large anomaly burdens across many services, with adservice and adservice2 among the highest. Per-component peak-minute analysis shows that many services have their worst per-minute anomaly counts near 21:59–22:00, while some components show high anomaly counts earlier in the window as well. These results narrow the search: there are likely two failure events — one near the later peak (around 21:59–22:00) and another earlier in the window (around ~21:50–21:55). We now need trace-level evidence to localize which service/pod is the downstream faulty component for each candidate failure minute and to determine whether the fault is service-level or container-level. Trace data (trace.csv) covers 21:30–21:59 UTC+8, so it can help confirm the later peak at 21:59 and earlier minutes up to 21:59. No root cause has been decided yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Inspect trace.csv for the candidate failure minutes. Do the following in one atomic step: Filter trace.csv to timestamps 2022-03-20 21:50:00+08:00 and 2022-03-20 21:59:00+08:00 (if a timestamp does not exist, return nothing for that timestamp but still process the other). For each of these timestamps, aggregate trace records by cmdb_id and compute: count_of_trace_rows, avg_value for each trace_name where trace_name contains 'duration' (e.g., trace.self.duration_mean or other duration features), and the max_value for those duration traces. Return two compact tables (one per timestamp) each limited to the top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by descending avg duration, with columns: timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, count_of_trace_rows_for_that_trace_name, avg_value, max_value. Additionally, return the list of unique trace_name values present in trace.csv (limit to 50). Keep outputs compact and at most 20 rows per timestamp."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metric anomalies at candidate minutes and found that the only anomalous metric rows returned for the selected top-10 cmdb_ids at 2022-03-20 21:50 and 21:59 are for cmdb_id 'adservice'. These anomalies are classified as 'high' and many examples are application-level KPIs (app.grpc.*, app.http.*, runtime.java_lang_*). However, trace analysis for the candidate minutes showed the largest latency traces are frontend -> checkoutservice calls (not adservice). This creates two possibilities: (1) adservice metrics are true anomalies and indicate adservice resource or application problems coincident with observed latency elsewhere, or (2) adservice anomalies are false positives caused by threshold artifact (many p05==p95==value entries) and the real latency-causing fault is elsewhere (e.g., checkoutservice or frontend). To distinguish these, we must examine resource-related KPIs and temporal patterns for adservice across the whole 21:30–22:00 window (not just the two minutes): specifically check whether adservice shows consecutive anomalies in container CPU/memory/network/fs KPIs and identify the earliest adservice anomaly timestamp and the set of kpis that first breached thresholds. If adservice resource KPIs show consecutive, strong breaches that start exactly at one of the candidate minutes, that supports adservice as a root cause; if not, adservice app-level KPI flags may be spurious and we should focus on frontend/checkoutservice resource KPIs and logs. Currently not enough evidence to finalize root cause or occurrence times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For cmdb_id 'adservice', use the precomputed global thresholds (p05/p95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name)) and the metric.csv data filtered to the incident window 2022-03-20 21:30:00 to 2022-03-20 22:00:00 (UTC+8). For each kpi_name of adservice present in the window compute: count_in_window, anomaly_count_high (value >= p95), anomaly_count_low (value <= p05), total_anomaly_count, earliest_anom_ts (earliest timestamp in window with an anomaly). Return a compact table of the top 20 adservice kpi_name rows ranked by total_anomaly_count with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_in_window, anomaly_count_high, anomaly_count_low, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anom_ts, p05, p95. Additionally return: the earliest anomaly timestamp across all adservice KPIs (single value) and the number of distinct adservice KPIs that had any anomaly in the window. Limit results to at most 20 rows."
}

Based on the metric, trace, and log analysis: sustained high container memory metrics on checkoutservice pods (notably checkoutservice-2) began at 2022-03-20 21:30:00+08:00 and correlate with trace latency spikes (largest per-minute trace max at 21:30 and additional peaks at ~21:50 and ~21:59). Logs show no explicit error_count/OOM entries in the provided logs, but metrics + traces consistently point to checkoutservice (pod-level) memory pressure causing degraded service and the observed failures. I therefore attribute both observed incidents to checkoutservice pod memory load.

